title HAWM0's host script becomes a Rish entrypoint over a bash worker
prompt Keaton asked to switch model effort to Sonnet 5 1M Low, then asked whether tools/hawm0_boot_onpath_host.sh (the prior turn's bash HAWM0 boot script) could be converted to a Rish script.
think Checked Rish's own real capabilities before attempting a literal port -- read manual/reference/rishi-language.md section 4 directly: `run` is blocking-only, returning a run record after the child exits; there is no backgrounding (`&`), no `trap`, no `wait`, and no native sleep-and-poll loop construct. The existing .sh script's whole shape (background the emulator, poll adb with a for-loop and sleep, trap-cleanup on exit) cannot port to pure Rish at all -- this is a real language limit, not a workaround to route around.
think Found the tree's own precedent for exactly this situation rather than inventing a new pattern: tools/lane_kvm_onpath_host.rish never does its own backgrounded QEMU boot -- it asserts preconditions, then makes one blocking `run ["bash" "-c" ...]` call into tools/proven_seat_g0c_lane_kvm.sh, which owns all the actual process management. Mirrored that split exactly rather than either (a) leaving the whole thing as one bash file with no Rish entrypoint at all, or (b) trying to force background/poll logic into Rish and hitting a wall.
think Renamed the original script to tools/hawm0_boot_worker.sh (the "guest" role, matching proven_seat_g0c_lane_kvm.sh's own naming sense) with zero logic changes -- only its header comment, now naming that it is not meant to be run directly and pointing at the new entrypoint. Wrote tools/hawm0_boot_onpath_host.rish fresh: three staged-precondition asserts (JDK, emulator binary, AVD .ini -- each checking a real file this same jail already staged and verified last turn), one `run` call to the worker, then asserts the worker's own output both succeeded and contains "GREEN" -- the same two-layer assertion shape lane_kvm_onpath_host.rish already uses (boot.ok AND boot.out contains "GREEN", not either alone).
think Ran the new .rish file directly inside this same jail as the real test, rather than only reading it for correctness -- it parsed clean and refused exactly where it should: the /dev/kvm assert failed loudly with the intended REFUSE message, proving the Rish syntax, the sequencing, and the assert wiring are all correct up to the one boundary this jail genuinely cannot cross. Independently confirmed (plain `test -x`/`test -f`) that the three staged-setup checks would each pass if /dev/kvm were present, since the assert chain stops at the first failure and the later checks never got to run in this jail.
think Updated the three living documents that named the old .sh path (ROADMAP.md's continuation paragraph, TASKS.md's own HAWM0 bullet, the mobile-emulation spec's HAWM0 rung row) to the new .rish entrypoint, each also naming the worker-file split and why it exists. Deliberately left the dated session log (20260716-131010) and its own session-logs/README.md row completely untouched -- they honestly recorded what existed at that stamp (a bare .sh script), and accrete-never-break means a later rename does not retroactively edit yesterday's own true record.
obs This was a genuine two-file answer to what looked like a one-file question, and naming that honestly mattered more than delivering a single .rish file that either silently dropped the polling logic or quietly wrapped the same bash script under a misleading "converted" label.
file tools/hawm0_boot_worker.sh -- renamed from hawm0_boot_onpath_host.sh; header rewritten to name its own worker role and point at the new entrypoint; zero logic changes
file tools/hawm0_boot_onpath_host.rish -- new; the host-facing Rish entrypoint, precondition asserts + one worker call + GREEN assert, run directly in this jail and confirmed to refuse correctly at /dev/kvm
file context/specs/two-dev-environments-and-mobile-emulation.md -- HAWM0 rung's remaining-step citation updated to the .rish entrypoint, naming the bash-worker split
file work-in-progress/TASKS.md -- HAWM0 bullet's remaining-step citation updated the same way, plus a dated note recording the conversion and its in-jail refuse-test
file work-in-progress/ROADMAP.md -- continuation paragraph's citation updated the same way
recommend keep-going -- the actual boot step is unchanged in substance (same worker logic, same preconditions, same GREEN/RED contract), only better-fronted; `rishi/bin/rishi run tools/hawm0_boot_onpath_host.rish` from a plain host terminal with /dev/kvm is still the one remaining human action.
